# Task and Process Management

## Lab Overview
This lab explores how use CLI to complete task management without using a GUI

## Objectives

- Understand how these capabilities are relevant to cybersecurity
- Identify the information types that are provided through use of commands
- Learn the different commands and their arguements for Task Management

## Key Concepts

| tasklist | displays processes that are running currently on a system, such as applications, background services, system processes |
| tasklist /FI | show processes that match a specific condition |
| taskkill /PID | terminates a process by its process ID number

## Environment

Platform: TryHackMe  
Operating System: Windows Server 2019
Instance: Windows CLI

## Lab Walkthrough

### Syntax: tasklist

C:\>tasklist

Image Name                     PID Session Name        Session#    Mem Usage 
========================= ======== ================ =========== ============
System Idle Process              0 Services                   0          8 K
System                           4 Services                   0         88 K
Registry                        84 Services                   0     50,700 K
smss.exe                       276 Services                   0      1,132 K
csrss.exe                      372 Services                   0      5,264 K
wininit.exe                    448 Services                   0      6,892 K
csrss.exe                      456 Console                    1      5,028 K
winlogon.exe                   516 Console                    1     11,144 K
services.exe                   584 Services                   0      7,492 K
lsass.exe                      592 Services                   0     16,108 K
svchost.exe                    704 Services                   0     23,432 K
fontdrvhost.exe                736 Console                    1      4,256 K
[...]
- each row shows a running process
- PID(numeric identifier for the that process)
- Session Name(shows the 'session a process belongs to such as background services or user session processes)
- Session #(Numberic ID of a session.Another way other than the Session name to distinguish between Service and Console session.)
- Mem Usage(amount of RAM in KB that each process is using)
- System Idle Process(represents unused CPU time)
- System(core Windows system process)
- Registry(tied to Windows registry in memory)
- smss.exe(session manager subsystem. Importnatn Windows startup/system process)
- csrss.exe(Client Server Runtime Process. Windows system process)
- wininit.exe(startup process)
- winlogon.exe(handles logon-related windows functions)
- services.exe( controls windows services)
- lsass.exe(Local Security Subsystem Service. handles authentication and security policy)
- svchost.exe(Windows runs services under this service)
- fontdrvhost.exe(Windows font driver host process)

### Syntax: taskkill /PID 2216
- terminated the process with PID identity 2216

## Security Relevance
- tasklist can show unexpected executables, duplicate processes and processes using an unusual amount of memory
- taskill can be used as a form of containment. malicious or abnormal processes can be termintated quickly
